NOTE TO SELF — read before finalizing:

This is a strict "all rights reserved" proprietary license, appropriate if Contextly
stays fully closed-source. Two other options worth considering once the direction
is clearer:

1. Business Source License (BSL) — source-available (anyone can read/audit the
   code) but not free to run as a competing commercial service until a set future
   date, after which it converts to a fully open license. This is the model
   context-mode (a similar/competing project) uses. Consider this if you want
   the trust and community benefit of visible source code without giving away
   your commercial advantage immediately.

2. MIT/Apache 2.0 (fully open source) — only makes sense if the actual business
   model is hosting/support/enterprise features rather than the core software
   itself, similar to how some dev tools monetize.

Decide this deliberately once you're closer to public launch — don't leave the
strict proprietary default in place by accident if the real intention is
source-available.
